#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:10
msgid "Racket"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:12
msgid ""
"Much like Python, Racket packages and modules have their own special build "
"system. To learn more about the specifics of Racket package system, please "
"refer to the `Racket Docs <https://docs.racket-lang.org/pkg/cmdline.html>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:18
msgid "Phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:20
msgid ""
"The ``RacketBuilder`` and ``RacketPackage`` base classes provides an "
"``install`` phase that can be overridden, corresponding to the use of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:23
msgid "$ raco pkg install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:29
msgid "Caveats"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:31
msgid ""
"In principle, ``raco`` supports a second, ``setup`` phase; however, we have "
"not implemented this separately, as in normal circumstances, ``install`` "
"also handles running ``setup`` automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:35
msgid ""
"Unlike Python, Racket currently on supports two installation scopes for "
"packages, user or system, and keeps a registry of installed packages at each "
"scope in its configuration files. This means we can't simply compose a "
"\"``RACKET_PATH``\" environment variable listing all of the places packages "
"are installed, and update this at will."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:40
msgid ""
"Unfortunately this means that all currently installed packages which extend "
"Racket via ``raco pkg install`` are accessible whenever Racket is accessible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/racketpackage.rst:43
msgid ""
"Additionally, because Spack does not implement uninstall hooks, uninstalling "
"a Spack  ``rkt-`` package will have no effect on the ``raco`` installed "
"packages visible to your Racket installation. Instead, you must manually run "
"``raco pkg remove`` to keep the two package managers in a mutually "
"consistent state."
msgstr ""
